<paragraph blockId="5.[264,1325,284,790]" pageId="5" pageNumber="6">
Remarks. 
<taxonomicName box="[431,629,684,709]" class="Insecta" family="Pipunculidae" genus="Elmohardyia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="6" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="nicaraguensis" status="sp. n.">
<emphasis box="[431,629,684,709]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="6">E. nicaraguensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[637,701,684,710]" pageId="5" pageNumber="6" rank="species">sp. n.</taxonomicNameLabel>
is near 
<taxonomicName authority="Hardy" authorityName="Hardy" box="[796,1035,684,710]" class="Insecta" family="Pipunculidae" genus="Elmohardyia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="6" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="replicata">
<emphasis box="[796,934,684,709]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="6">E. replicata</emphasis>
(Hardy)
</taxonomicName>
in the similar pattern of abdominal pruinosity and surstyli shape. It is different by the shape of the hypandrium, notably by the extremely developed external side of the phallic guide.
</paragraph>
